{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A request whose signature does not match its body is rejected with a 401 response; the body is not forwarded.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is handler-to-queue handoff: the same request must both return 401 and avoid enqueue. A unit test of only HMAC comparison misses forwarding side effects. Higher levels were rejected because behavior text only requires request validation + local module interaction, not real OS/network/subprocess or any AI output.","test_description":"Run handler with an in-process HTTP request fixture containing a bad `X-Signature-256`, assert 401, and assert queue writer/spool module was not called and queue size unchanged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"An event is written to the persistent queue before the HTTP 200 acknowledgment is returned to the sender.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is an ordering guarantee across HTTP handler and persistence module. Needs real wiring to the persistent queue adapter (local DB/filesystem is enough). System was considered but rejected: behavior text does not require real network/subprocess effects, only internal ordering before response.","test_description":"Use an in-process server/handler wired to the real local persistence-backed queue; instrument timestamps/hooks so test asserts durable write completes before 200 is emitted.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The handler returns the HTTP response without waiting for downstream processing of the event to finish.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Bug appears at module boundary between enqueue/dispatch and downstream worker completion. A single-function unit test can miss await/Promise chaining mistakes. System rejected because requirement is about internal async decoupling, not real OS/network behavior.","test_description":"Wire handler to a downstream processor stub that blocks on a controllable promise; assert HTTP response is returned before that promise resolves, while event remains queued/processing continues asynchronously.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The response arrives within 3 seconds wall-clock time even when downstream processing of earlier events is slow and concurrent.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This explicitly depends on wall-clock latency under concurrency, which is sensitive to real HTTP server behavior, event-loop scheduling, socket/backpressure, and timeout behavior. In-process mocks can hide real latency failures.","test_description":"Start the real Node HTTP service process, create concurrent load with earlier slow events, send a new valid webhook over real HTTP, and assert end-to-end response time < 3s wall-clock.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"An event whose ID was already received is not written to the queue a second time.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Dedup correctness is at handler + idempotency store/queue boundary. Unit logic alone can miss persistence/index/transaction handoff bugs. System rejected because behavior text does not require OS/network/subprocess; local persistent module wiring is sufficient.","test_description":"With real local queue/idempotency storage wiring, send the same event ID twice and assert first enqueue succeeds, second is treated as duplicate and no second persisted queue record appears.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_